<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06072005 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06072005 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SEMICONDUCTOR; COMPANY; SALE; DECREASE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Hurt by a sluggish economy and a slow market for computer chips, NationalSemiconductor Corp. on Monday reported a sharp drop in sales for the thirdquarter.;    The Santa Clara chip maker said revenues for the three monthsended Feb. 24 fell to $387 million from $404 million in the year-ago period.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  NATIONAL SEMI'S SALES FELL SHARPLY IN THIRDQUARTER  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The company was saved from posting a loss by a restructuring credit of $21million related to the sale of its plant in Puyallup, Wash. National said ithad been too conservative in setting aside funds to cover the cost of sellingthe facility, which was purchased in February by Matusushita Electronics Corp.of Japan.;    With the credit, National recorded a profit of $5 million forthe quarter, or 2 cents per share, compared with a loss of $10.2 million, or12 cents per share, for the third quarter of 1990. Without the credit,National would have shown an operating loss of about $15 million.;    CharlesE. Sporck, president and chief executive, blamed the sales drop on &quot;thecurrent recessionary environment&quot; combined with &quot;seasonal weaknesses wetraditionally face in the third quarter.&quot; However, he added that an increasein chip orders during the past three months should result in a profitablefourth quarter.;    Mel Phelps, a semiconductor industry analyst withHambrecht andamp; Quist Inc. in San Francisco, said National appeared to besuffering the effect of slowdowns in a number of chip markets, particularlyautos and minicomputers. Chips destined for automobiles account for between 12and 15 percent of National's sales.;    Phelps described the third-quarterresults as &quot;a real mixed bag.&quot; But he said the company appears to have writtenoff most of its losses and is well-positioned for a broad recovery underGilbert F. Amelio, who is due to take over as president and chief executive inMay.;    Amelio now shares the office with Sporck, who announced plans toretire in January after nearly 24 years at National's helm.;    NationalSemiconductor stock closed at $7.75 Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, up13 cents.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  TOM SCHMITZ, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910312  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  341  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday March 12, 199100072005,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>